    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the `sys_report` row that
    declares the "Case Count by Status" donut/pie chart report on the
    `x_casemgmt_case` custom table inside the scoped application `x_casemgmt`.

    Per AAP Section 0.5.1 (File-by-File Transformation Plan) verbatim:
        servicenow-case-management-poc/reports/x_casemgmt_case_count_by_status.xml
            CREATE  Source: -
            Key Changes: "Donut grouped by status"

    Per AAP Section 0.4.1 (Refactored Structure Planning) verbatim:
        Agent Workspace Dashboard widget inventory includes
            "donut chart for 'Case count by status'"

    Per AAP Section 0.4.4 (User Interface Design) verbatim:
        Agent Workspace Dashboard - "donut chart for 'Case count by status'"

    Per AAP Section 0.7.3 (Validation Framework) verbatim, this report is
    one of the data sources for Gate 6 (Dashboards):
        "Both dashboards render with synthetic data ... All widgets display
         data; no broken report references"

    Per AAP Section 0.3.1 (Exhaustively In Scope) verbatim:
        servicenow-case-management-poc/reports/sys_report_x_casemgmt_case_count_by_status.xml
            "donut on case.status"

    THIS FILE'S ROLE IN THE OVERALL POC
    ===================================
    This report is the at-a-glance status distribution donut chart shown
    on the Agent Workspace dashboard
    (../dashboards/pa_dashboards_x_casemgmt_agent_workspace.xml). It sits
    alongside two list widgets ("My Open Cases" and "My Overdue Tasks")
    to give an agent a complete operational view at login:

      - "My Open Cases" list (../reports/x_casemgmt_my_open_cases.xml)
        shows the agent's PERSONAL queue of actionable cases.
      - "My Overdue Tasks" list (../reports/x_casemgmt_my_overdue_tasks.xml)
        shows the agent's PERSONAL list of late tasks.
      - THIS donut shows the ENTIRE TEAM's case backlog distribution by
        status. The agent uses it to spot bottlenecks (e.g., a Pending
        slice that has grown large) and to identify pull-work
        opportunities (e.g., an Open slice with unassigned cases that
        the agent could absorb).

    The two list widgets are filtered per-viewer via gs.getUserID(); THIS
    donut is intentionally UNFILTERED. The complementary perspective is
    the design intent per AAP Section 0.4.4: agents need both their
    personal queue AND the team-wide picture.

    SEMANTIC SOURCE-SIDE ANCHOR (READ-ONLY, NOT BYTE-FOR-BYTE PORTED)
    =================================================================
    The semantic ancestors of this report in the existing ArkCase
    codebase are three Java artifacts in the case-file-plugin:

      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/
        java/com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseFile.java
        Lines 141-142:
            @Column(name = "cm_case_status")
            private String status;
        ArkCase tracks case status as a free-form String column on the
        `acm_case_file` MySQL table. The ServiceNow target normalizes
        this to a Choice field with exactly six values per AAP Section
        0.5.7 (Draft, Open, In Progress, Pending, Resolved, Closed)
        defined in ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml. The
        <group_by>status</group_by> below references this Choice field
        by element name; the donut renders one slice per Choice label.

      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/
        java/com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseByStatusDto.java
        Lines 33-57:
            public class CaseByStatusDto {
                private String status;
                private int    count;
                ... getters and setters ...
            }
        The DTO that ArkCase produced when aggregating cases by status -
        a (status, count) tuple consumed by Pentaho-backed reports. The
        ServiceNow target replaces this DTO + Pentaho pipeline with a
        native sys_report whose `<group_by>status</group_by>` plus
        `<aggregate>COUNT</aggregate>` produce the same tuple shape
        directly via the platform's GlideAggregate engine - no DTO,
        no external BI tool, no Solr facet. The dashboard widget renders
        the (status, count) pairs as donut slices.

      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/
        java/com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/state/AcmCasesState.java
        Lines 32-45:
            public class AcmCasesState extends StateOfModule {
                private Long numberOfCases;
                ...
            }
        ArkCase exposed a single-cell case-count via this state-carrier;
        the ServiceNow equivalent at THIS report's level is the SUM of
        all donut slices (i.e., total count across the six statuses).
        The dashboard widget can render that total in the chart center
        based on the aggregated COUNT - a UX convention handled by the
        widget rendering layer, not THIS report definition.

      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/
        java/com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/
        CaseSummaryByStatusAndTimePeriodDto.java:
            private String                  timePeriod;
            private List<CaseByStatusDto>   caseByStatusDtoList;
        ArkCase aggregated cases by status across time periods using
        a custom DTO consumed by Pentaho BI reports. The aggregator was
        Pentaho-side, NOT JPA-side. The ServiceNow target replaces
        Pentaho-driven time-period aggregation with platform-native
        sys_report records (this file plus the seven sibling reports
        in this folder), all powered by ServiceNow's native GlideAggregate
        engine instead of an external BI engine - per AAP Section 0.1.2
        ("Reporting transformation: Pentaho BI + Solr aggregates ->
        ServiceNow Reports + Performance Analytics-style dashboards").

    DESIGN DECISIONS LOCKED IN BY THIS FILE
    =======================================
      - Aggregation discipline (AAP Section 0.5.1, this report's row):
        type = pie. Per agent-prompt Mandatory Field Specification,
        chart-type reports populate <type>, <group_by>, and <aggregate>;
        they leave <field_list/> and <aggregation_source/> empty. The
        rendered output is one donut/pie chart with one slice per
        distinct value of `status`.

      - Group-by discipline (agent-prompt Rule 4 verbatim):
        <group_by>status</group_by>. The Choice field defined in
        ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_status.xml. The six slices
        correspond to the six Choice values defined in
        ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml: Draft, Open, In Progress,
        Pending, Resolved, Closed (Title Case match required).

      - Filter discipline (agent-prompt Rule 5 verbatim):
        <filter/> empty. This report counts ALL cases regardless of
        assignment, type, or priority. The complementary "My Open
        Cases" list report (../reports/x_casemgmt_my_open_cases.xml)
        provides the per-viewer filtered view; THIS donut intentionally
        does NOT filter so agents can see the entire team's status
        distribution.

      - Aggregation discipline (agent-prompt Rule 6 verbatim):
        <aggregate>COUNT</aggregate>. Counts records per status bucket.
        <aggregation_source/> empty (COUNT does not require a numeric
        source field; it counts rows, not values).

      - Field-list discipline (agent-prompt Rule 9 verbatim):
        <field_list/> empty. Chart reports do NOT specify a field list;
        the field list is meaningful only for `type=list` reports per
        the sibling pattern in ../reports/x_casemgmt_my_open_cases.xml
        (which uses <field_list>number,subject,priority,status,opened_date</field_list>).
        For chart reports, the chart-type and group-by fully determine
        what is rendered.

      - Per-viewer semantics: this report does NOT reference any
        user-specific identity (e.g., gs.getUserID()); it returns the
        SAME aggregated counts for every viewer. Therefore:
          1) The platform does not need to re-compute the aggregate
             per-user, only per-cache-cycle. <is_real_time>false</is_real_time>
             below permits cached evaluation.
          2) Different roles see the same numbers (modulo what their
             ACL permits them to read). For a `case_viewer`, all six
             slices appear (read-all ACL). For a `case_agent`, only
             slices for cases assigned to them or their group appear
             (assigned-only ACL per AAP Section 0.5.6). For a
             `case_manager`, all six slices appear (full ACL).

      - Why not "type=donut": ServiceNow's sys_report.type vocabulary
        does NOT include a literal "donut" enum value; the canonical
        round-aggregate chart type is "pie". The platform renders a
        donut-style chart (pie with center hole) automatically when
        a sys_report of type=pie is embedded in a modern Dashboard
        widget - the donut/pie distinction is a presentation-layer
        decision made at the widget level, not the report level.
        Cross-version safety per AAP Section 0.4.2 ("Yokohama-and-later
        feature floor"): `pie` exists in every ServiceNow release this
        POC targets; `donut` does not exist as a sys_report.type value
        in any release.

      - Why both this donut AND a parallel bar chart of the same
        aggregation: per AAP Section 0.4.4 the Manager View dashboard
        carries a separate "All Cases by Status" bar chart
        (../reports/x_casemgmt_all_cases_by_status.xml). Both reports
        share identical <table>, <group_by>, <aggregate>, and (empty)
        <filter>; they differ only in <type> (pie vs. bar) and in
        which dashboard consumes them (Agent Workspace vs. Manager
        View). The duplication is INTENTIONAL per AAP Section 0.4.4
        to give each audience the visualization optimized for their
        decision-making style:
          - Agents: at-a-glance proportional view (donut) - easier to
            scan visually for an "is the queue balanced?" judgment.
          - Managers: comparative magnitude view (bar) - easier to
            read absolute counts for capacity-planning decisions.
        Both reports MUST be present; do NOT consolidate them into
        one shared report. Per AAP Section 0.5.2 cross-file dependencies,
        both reports load AFTER tables/dictionary/choices and BEFORE
        their respective dashboards.

      - Cache discipline: <is_real_time>false</is_real_time>. The
        platform may cache the aggregated counts and refresh on a
        cycle (typically 5 minutes for the Reports module). For a
        POC dashboard with 10 demo cases this distinction is
        cosmetic; for a production case-management deployment with
        thousands of cases it materially affects dashboard load
        time. The default-off setting matches the sibling reports
        (../reports/x_casemgmt_my_open_cases.xml,
         ../reports/x_casemgmt_avg_time_to_close.xml,
         ../reports/x_casemgmt_cases_opened_30d.xml).

      - Chart-size discipline: <chart_size>medium</chart_size>. The
        platform-default rendering size for embedded dashboard widgets.
        Matches the sibling reports.

      - Scope binding: <sys_scope>x_casemgmt</sys_scope> and
        <sys_package source="x_casemgmt">x_casemgmt</sys_package>
        bind THIS record to the same scoped-app row that the parent
        sys_app record (../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml)
        publishes. Cross-file consistency: the sibling reports
        (x_casemgmt_my_open_cases.xml, x_casemgmt_my_overdue_tasks.xml,
        x_casemgmt_avg_time_to_close.xml, x_casemgmt_cases_opened_30d.xml)
        use identical scope-reference values, ensuring all reports
        resolve to the same sys_app row at preview time. Reference-
        by-name not reference-by-sys_id per AAP Section 0.7.2
        (no hardcoded sys_ids constraint).

      - <sys_id> determinism: the value
        32ae52ab8735ea76587edee6130abc06 is the lowercase MD5 of the
        canonical record name "x_casemgmt_case_count_by_status". This
        matches the convention documented in
        ../reports/x_casemgmt_my_open_cases.xml lines 219-236
        (md5("x_casemgmt_my_open_cases") = ee04fa982b136ad35c6fe1512826f6ab),
        ../reports/x_casemgmt_avg_time_to_close.xml lines 233-247
        (md5("x_casemgmt_avg_time_to_close") = 79fabb5f5754b629205b2382face3ebb),
        and ../reports/x_casemgmt_cases_opened_30d.xml lines 71-84
        (md5("x_casemgmt_cases_opened_30d") = 95b2127b026a92ba5e041a8d4d7277ec).
        Deterministic derivation makes the Update Set re-importable
        on a fresh PDI without sys_id collisions: re-importing the
        same XML on the same or any future PDI resolves the same
        sys_id and idempotently updates the same report row rather
        than creating a duplicate. This stability is REQUIRED because
        the Agent Workspace dashboard
        (../dashboards/pa_dashboards_x_casemgmt_agent_workspace.xml)
        references THIS report by `<name>x_casemgmt_case_count_by_status</name>`,
        and the dashboard widget binding must resolve consistently
        across re-imports.

    CROSS-DEPENDENCY GRAPH
    ======================
    DEPENDS ON (must load earlier in the Update Set):
      - ../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml
      - ../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml
      - ../tables/x_casemgmt_case.xml                  (parent table)
      - ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_status.xml
            (defines the Choice field used in <group_by>)
      - ../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml
            (defines the six status Choice values rendered as slices:
             Draft, Open, In Progress, Pending, Resolved, Closed)

    REFERENCED BY (must load later in the Update Set):
      - ../dashboards/pa_dashboards_x_casemgmt_agent_workspace.xml
        References THIS report by `<name>x_casemgmt_case_count_by_status</name>`,
        NOT by sys_id, so a fresh-PDI re-import correctly resolves the
        widget binding to the deterministic MD5-derived sys_id above.

    PARALLEL REPORT (different chart type, different dashboard):
      - ../reports/x_casemgmt_all_cases_by_status.xml
        Same aggregation (group by status, COUNT), but rendered as
        type=bar and consumed by the Manager View dashboard. The
        duplication is intentional per AAP Section 0.4.4.

    SEED-DATA DEPENDENCY (Validation Gate 6 pass condition):
      - ../seed-data/cases/x_casemgmt_case_demo_*.xml must include
        cases spanning all six statuses (Draft, Open, In Progress,
        Pending, Resolved, Closed) per AAP Section 0.4.1 demo-data
        plan. Without seed cases in each status, the donut renders
        with fewer than six slices (or none at all), which would
        fail the "All widgets display data" criterion of Validation
        Gate 6 (AAP Section 0.7.3) even though the report DEFINITION
        itself is correct. The AAP-prescribed seed plan satisfies
        this requirement: demo_01 (Draft), demo_02 (Open), demo_03
        (In Progress), demo_04 (Pending), demo_05 (Resolved),
        demo_06 (Closed) - one case per status for General Inquiry,
        plus four more Complaint cases extending coverage. Six
        slices guaranteed.

    UPDATE-SET ORDERING
    ===================
    Per AAP Section 0.5.2 (Cross-File Dependencies):
      - AFTER tables, dictionary, choices.
      - AFTER seed-data so that running the report yields non-empty
        results during validation.
      - BEFORE the Agent Workspace dashboard so that dashboard widget
        binding resolves.

    AUTHORING-RULES COMPLIANCE
    ==========================
      - AAP Section 0.7.2 verbatim:
          "No-hardcoded-sys_id constraint. Anywhere - flows, ACL
           conditions, scripts, seed data, UI Policies, UI Actions,
           Business Rules. Every cross-reference is resolved by
           GlideRecord lookup against a stable human-readable key
           (name, user_name, number, role_label)."
        This file: <sys_scope> and <sys_package> resolve by scope
        name; <sys_id> is THIS record's own primary key (not a
        hardcoded reference to another record), deterministically
        derived as MD5(name). <table> resolves by table name. The
        Choice values "Draft", "Open", etc., are NOT references to
        sys_id values - they are Choice labels resolved at render
        time. All compliant.

      - AAP Section 0.7.2 verbatim:
          "No-PII constraint. Synthetic data only."
        This file: report definition contains no PII; the report
        merely AGGREGATES rows from a table. Whatever PII or non-PII
        data is in those rows is the seed-data agent's responsibility
        to keep synthetic. The report definition is PII-free.

      - AAP Section 0.7.2 verbatim:
          "Scope-namespace exclusivity: every artifact ... must live
           in the auto-assigned `x_casemgmt` namespace; zero global-
           scope writes are permitted."
        This file: <name> is `x_casemgmt_case_count_by_status`;
        <table> is `x_casemgmt_case`; <sys_scope> and <sys_package>
        bind to the scoped app. Zero global-scope writes.

      - AAP Section 0.7.2 verbatim:
          "Email-disabled constraint."
        This file: does NOT include any scheduled-email-delivery
        configuration. <is_scheduled>false</is_scheduled>. The only
        consumer is the dashboard widget.

      - AAP Section 0.7.2 verbatim:
          "Single-Update-Set deliverable constraint."
        This file: one of the records that compose the final Update
        Set XML at ../update-set/x_casemgmt_case_management_update_set.xml.

      - AAP Section 0.7.2 verbatim:
          "Minimal-Change Clause. Build only what is specified in the
           user's prompt."
        This file: implements exactly one report row per AAP Section
        0.5.1; no additional fields beyond those mandated by the
        agent prompt; no new dimensions or aggregations beyond
        group-by-status COUNT.

